  "prompt": "What if a cricket ball hits a batsman\u2019s helmet and then goes to the boundary?",
  "response": "In the sport of cricket, if a ball hits a batsman's helmet and subsequently goes to the boundary, the way runs are awarded can depend on the specific circumstances surrounding the incident.\n\n1. **If the ball strikes the helmet worn by the batsman and then goes to the boundary without touching the ground before crossing the boundary**: In this case, the ball is considered a boundary, and the batting team is awarded four runs.\n\n2. **If the ball strikes the helmet and then bounces before crossing the boundary**: The batting team will also be awarded four runs, as it is treated as a boundary off the bat, regardless of where the ball has struck (including the helmet).\n\n3. **If the ball hits the helmet and is deemed a no-ball (for instance, if it was a bouncer that has exceeded the height limit during a delivery)**: In a no-ball situation, the batting team is still awarded runs for the boundary, in addition to any extra runs from the no-ball.\n\nIn any situation where the helmet is involved, if the ball has struck the batsman and is deemed to have been played by them (as a result of being an intentional shot, etc.), it can affect the run counts the batting team is awarded. \n\nHowever, if the ball strikes the helmet but there is a threat to the players' safety, such as the bat being struck in an improper manner or other similar concerns, the umpire may make additional decisions regarding handling the situation to ensure safety is prioritized.\n\nFor exact rulings, it's always best to consult the Laws of Cricket or the respective governing body's rules.",
